    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>The examples use association lists with explicit semiring operations. Kidney and Wu work with free semimodule monads in Haskell, using type classes to abstract over the semiring. For example: the counting example above uses an explicit loop with <code>set-cdr!</code> to merge duplicates. In the paper, this is the free semimodule's universal property — the unique algebra morphism that folds a formal sum into a concrete semiring value. The computation is the same; the universality guarantee is not.</p>
    <p>Every example is <strong class="text-green-400">Simplified</strong>.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 text-center text-sm text-gray-400 mt-10">
      Ready for the real thing? <a href="https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3473577">Read the paper</a> (ICFP 2021). Start at §3 for the free semimodule monad, §5 for the semiring-parameterized search.
